# Encapsulated Capability Rule

When adding new functional capabilities, prefer implementing them as **encapsulated parts** instead of expanding existing page controllers with large inline blocks.

## Preferred approach

- Put reusable parsing, rendering, and behavior in dedicated shared modules when the capability appears on more than one page
- Keep page-level files focused on wiring, state flow, and event hookup
- Prefer small single-purpose classes or helpers over long procedural blocks
- Prefer shared CSS/JS assets for repeated UI capabilities instead of duplicating the same implementation in multiple pages

## Apply this especially when

- The same feature appears in both `object_motion` and `trajectory_player`
- A modal, overlay, gallery, zoom viewer, or other self-contained UI is being added
- The new behavior can reasonably be tested in isolation

## Avoid

- Copy-pasting the same modal or viewer logic into multiple page scripts
- Growing a page controller with large feature-specific rendering code when that code can live in its own module
- Mixing unrelated new capabilities into existing functions when a focused helper or component boundary would keep the code clearer
